The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	New Delhi: Joshna Chinappa tamed giant-killer Gaby Schmohl of Switzerland in straight sets to win the German Ladies Open and earn her fourth WISPA Tour title at Saarbrucken-Gudingen. The second seed Chinappa outplayed Schmohl 11-6, 11-7, 11-6 in a 22-minute final on Sunday. In the quarter final, Chinappa had routed eighth seed Carrie Ramsey of England and then beat French qualifier Melissa Alves in the semi-final.        
	Islamabad: The National Assembly Standing Committee on Sports Monday recommended the PCB to review the bans and fines slapped on seven players, saying that some of them, including former captains Younis Khan and Mohammed Yousuf, have not been treated fairly. PCB chairman Ejaz Butt promptly accepted the recommendations and said the board would review the ban and fines imposed on the players.        
	New Delhi: Sharath Kamals led the Indian mens team to their second successive victory, a 3-0 defeat of Canada but their women counterparts went down 1-3 to Malaysia in the World Team Table Tennis Championships in Moscow Monday.       
	Shivika up  
	Calcutta: City girl Shivika Burman made the second round of the ITF womens meet in Durban, with a 5-7, 6-4, 6-2 defeat of Hungarys Blanka Szavay.      
	Monza: Indias Armaan Ebrahim jostled through to an impressive fifth-spot finish in the FIA Formula Two Championship race after starting from the back of the grid following a disappointing qualifying session.       
	HAL promoted  
	Bangalore: Hindustan Aeronautics Limited Monday became the second side to qualify for the I-League top flight after playing out a 1-1 draw against Sesa Football Academy of Goa in their final match of the second division.  
	SSP poor show  
	Wentworth: Golfer S.S.P. Chowrasia rose five rungs to sign off tied 34th after carding an even-par 71 in the fourth and final round of the European Tours BMW PGA Championships. Englands Simon Khan (66) won the title with a total of six-under 278.   
	Rowing meet  
	Calcutta: South Point High School A beat La Martiniere for Boys A by 2.1 minutes in the Senior Boys Fours event at the BRC Students Rowing Championship being held at the Rabindra Sarobar. In the Senior Girls Fours event, South Point B beat Ashok Hall by 2.22 minutes. In the Senior Boys Fours event, Lake View School defeated La Martiniere for Boys B by 1.56 minutes.                                                                                                                                                  
